Recursion is the core of Dynamic Programming so coming up with recursive equation for any problem can be challenging. So here's a flow of a how a Recursion ends up being a 6 line solution.

**Recursion :**
To come up with the recursive equation we need to think on how many ways are there to buy a ticket.

*Scenario :*
*When our guy walks into the station to get ticket, he has to make choice between picking tickets.
He has a note in his hand to see what all days he is travelling.
So, **like a genius,** he looks at his notebook and thinks if he bought which ticket today, he might endup paying less in the year.
He thinks of buying a ticket today by looking at tomorrow's tickets at his disposal. **Oh wait!** now he thinks of the day after tomorrow and continues till last day of year!*

*Turns out, if he bought ticket everyother day in consecutive days of travell, the ticket price is cheap for a week pass than buying it for everyday of the week*

**He thinks about future and decides what to do today!**
`min cost of ticket` = `what ticket he might buy today` + `minimum price for the rest of the days`

which translates to,
```
minCost = min({ 
				oneDayPass + exceptToday,
				oneWeekPass + expectThisWeek,
				oneMonthPass, expectThisMonth 
			})
```

Which in code translates to,
```
// Calculate for today ie i
// Recursive eqaution
minCost = min({
				cost[0] + calculate(i + 1),
				cost[1] + calculate(i + 7),
				cost[2] + calculate(i + 30)
})
```

Recursion code,
```
class Solution {
public:
    int calculate(vector<int> &days, vector<int> &costs, int i, vector <bool> map) {
        if( i > 365)    // Reached the end of year!!
            return 0;
        if(!map[i])
            return calculate(days, costs, i+1, map);    // If he ain't travelling, goes to next day without buying any ticket
        return min({
            costs[0] + calculate(days, costs, i+1, map),
            costs[1] + calculate(days, costs, i+7, map),
            costs[2] + calculate(days, costs, i+30, map)
        });
    }

    int mincostTickets(vector<int>& days, vector<int>& costs) {
        vector <bool> map(366, false);    // To keep track the days he ain't travelling
        for(auto x: days)
            map[x] = true;   // Only the travelling days are marked
        int x = calculate(days, costs, 0, map);
        return x;
    }
};
```

*Now he figures out that, he is unneccesarily calculating for everyday repeatedly!
He thinks even smart know! Every time he calucates for a day, **he jots it down on the notebook**!*

**Recursion with memoization :**
All we need to do is introduce memo variable to avoid repeated calculations
```
class Solution {
public:
    int rec(vector<int> &days, vector<int> &costs, int i, vector <bool> map, vector <int>& memo) {
        if( i > 365)
            return 0;
        if(memo[i] != -1)
            return memo[i]; // Already calculated
        if(!map[i])
            return memo[i] = rec(days, costs, i+1, map, memo);
        return memo[i] = min({
            costs[0] + rec(days, costs, i+1, map, memo),
            costs[1] + rec(days, costs, i+7, map, memo),
            costs[2] + rec(days, costs, i+30, map, memo)
        });
    }

    int mincostTickets(vector<int>& days, vector<int>& costs) {
        vector <bool> map(366, false);
        vector <int> memo(366, -1);
        for(auto x: days)
            map[x] = true;
        int x = rec(days, costs, 0, map, memo);
        return x;
    }
};
```

*He figures out, because he already has the reapeated calculations jotted, he can just begin from the end and whatever price he ends up paying for today, will be the min cost for year!*

**Iterative DP : top down**
Can be written as bottom up, but that would equation will change. To maintain regularity and the proof of recursion equation leading to DP I'm using top-down.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int mincostTickets(vector<int>& days, vector<int>& costs) {
        int n = 367;
        vector <bool> map(n , false);
        vector <int> dp(n , 0);
        for(auto x: days)
            map[x] = true;
        for(int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--){
            dp[i] = dp[min(n - 1, i + 1)];
            if(map[i]){ 
                dp[i] = min({
                    costs[0] + dp[min(n - 1, i + 1)],
                    costs[1] + dp[min(n - 1, i + 7)],
                    costs[2] + dp[min(n - 1, i + 30)]
                });
            }
        }
        return dp[0];
    }
};
```


**6 lines DP Solution :**
*Let's make it look like a PRO!!!*
By the way, this is actually slower than the previous because set searching is expensive(computationally) over index array search
```
    int mincostTickets(vector<int>& days, vector<int>& costs) {
        int n = 367;
        unordered_set <int> map(days.begin(), days.end());
        vector <int> dp(n , 0);
        for(int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--)
            dp[i] = map.find(i) == map.end() ? dp[min(n - 1, i + 1)] : min({ costs[0] + dp[min(n - 1, i + 1)], costs[1] + dp[min(n - 1, i + 7)], costs[2] + dp[min(n - 1, i + 30)] });
        return dp[0];
    }
```

