solutions.content:
# Intuition
At any index $$idx$$, we have 3 choices:
- Buy a ticket for 1 day
- Buy a ticket for 7 days
- Buy a ticket for 30 days
We have to find the **optimal set of choices** we should make to spend the least amount of money and complete all our travel plans. 

```
Suppose f(0) means the minimum cost incurred if you buy a pass
at the 0-th index in the array:[1,10,15]

At index 0:
Total cost if you get a 1 day pass= costs[0] + f(1) //because you need to buy another ticket at index=1
Total cost if you get a 7 day pass= costs[1] + f(1) //because the ticket you buy on day 1 will expire after day 6
f(0)= Math.min(1 day pass, 7 day pass)

As the 7 day pass expires on day 6, you still have to calculate f(10)
```
Doesn't this repetitive nature of function calls hint at a DP solution? 

# Approach
Define a function:
```
function memo(index){}
```
where $$memo(index)$$ means the minimum amount of money spent to complete your travel plans, if you start at the day at $$index$$ position in the array.

As we're using only one parameter, we need a **1d dp array** to memoise results calculated by $$memo()$$

To deal with the availability of passes, assume you only had the option of a 1 day pass. How would memo function be called recursively?
```
memo(index){
  int buy1DayPass = costs[0] + memo(index+1);
  return buy1DayPass;
}
```
What changed do you need to make to account for the 7/30 day passes?
**Just call memo(day after your current ticket expires)**
```
If the array is: [1,5,10,20,22,50,60] and you had to calculate memo(2),
it would be:

memo(2){ // buy on day 10
  int buy30DayPass= costs[2]+ memo(5)//buy on day 50
}
```
As $$memo(5)$$ returns the minimum cost incurred if you **start from the 50th day**, you will have the cost incurred if you buy a 30 day pass on the 10th day *if the only available option was a 30 day pass.*

Just have to compute the minimum of all three choices.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(n)$$
We are calling each function only once before we store its result. 

- Space complexity:
$$O(n)$$

# Code
```java []
class Solution {

    public int mincostTickets(int[] days, int[] costs) {
        Integer[] dp = new Integer[days.length];
        return f(dp, days, costs, 0);
    }

    public int f(Integer[] dp, int[] nums, int[] costs, int idx) {
        if (idx == nums.length) {
            return 0;
        }
        if (dp[idx] != null) {
            return dp[idx];
        }

        // Buy a 1-day pass:
        int one = costs[0] + f(dp, nums, costs, idx + 1);

        // Buy a 7-day pass:
        int week = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        int k = idx;
        while (k < nums.length) {
            if (nums[idx] + 6 >= nums[k]) {
                k++;
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }
        week = costs[1] + f(dp, nums, costs, k);

        // Buy a 30-day pass:
        int month = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        k = idx;
        while (k < nums.length) {
            if (nums[idx] + 29 >= nums[k]) {
                k++;
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }
        month = costs[2] + f(dp, nums, costs, k);

        int ret = Math.min(one, Math.min(week, month));
        return dp[idx] = ret; 
    }
}

```
