solutions.content:
Idea is quite simple and it is based on the fact that at ``i-th`` day we can be in 3 possible conditions to minimize expenses:
* we buy 1-day pass, then min cost is ``1-day pass + min cost the day before`` i.e. ``costs[0] + minCost[i]``
* it is last day of 7-day pass, then min cost is ``7-day pass + min cost the day before we bought it`` i.e. ``costs[1] + minCost[i7]``
* it is last day of 30-day pass, then min cost is ``30-day pass + min cost the day before we bought it`` i.e. ``costs[2] + minCost[i30]``

``i7`` and ``i30`` are indices of the day when week or month window starts and are being advanced as we go and ``minCost`` is where we keep min cost for every day. Min cost for ``i-th`` day is kept in ``minCost[i+1]`` so that min cost at day before ``i-th`` day is ``minCost[i]``. If there is no day before day/week/month window min cost will be 0 i.e. ``minCost[0]=0``.

When we done the answer will be the last element in ``minCost``.

```
    public int mincostTickets(int[] days, int[] costs) {
        int[] minCost = new int[days.length + 1]; // DP to keep min cost at i + 1 day
        for (int i = 0, i7 = 0, i30 = 0; i < days.length; i++) {
            while (days[i] - days[i7] >= 7) i7++;    // advance week start
            while (days[i] - days[i30] >= 30) i30++; // advance month start
            int daily = costs[0] + minCost[i];
            int weekly = costs[1] + minCost[i7];
            int monthly = costs[2] + minCost[i30];
            minCost[i + 1] = Math.min(daily, Math.min(weekly, monthly));
        }
        return minCost[minCost.length - 1];
    }
```

