# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
**Explanation 1: DP**
1. Try to decode the problem and think for a recursive solution.
2. There are **three options** in this problem:
- Option 1: Take 1 day pass for each day
- Option 2: Take a 7 days pass for 7 consecutive days in a year.
- Option 3: Take a 30 days pass for 30 consecutive days in a year.
3.Let us see an example for better understanding:
**days[] = {2,5}, costs[] = {1,4,25}**

Here is the recursion tree for this example:
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e113f90d-6946-45b5-86fe-c7996a238f43_1689179197.6838899.png)

# Complexity
- Time complexity: **O(1)**
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The size of our dp vector is days.size() + 1, we know that in a year, there are 365 days (as per this question, leap year is not considered), therefore size of our dp vector can be atmost 365 + 1 = 366, this can obviously be accessed in a constant time.

- Space complexity: **O(1)**
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:

    int solveMem(vector<int>& days, vector<int>& costs, vector<int>& dp, int index)
    {
        if(index >= days.size()) return 0;

        if(dp[index] != -1) return dp[index];

        //1 day pass
        int option1 = costs[0] + solveMem(days, costs, dp, index + 1);

        int i;

        //7 days pass
        for(i = index; i < days.size() && days[i] < days[index] + 7; i++);
        int option2 = costs[1] + solveMem(days, costs, dp, i);

        //30 days pass
        for(i = index; i < days.size() && days[i] < days[index] + 30; i++);
        int option3 = costs[2] + solveMem(days, costs, dp, i);

        dp[index] = min(option1, min(option2, option3));

        return dp[index];
    }

    int mincostTickets(vector<int>& days, vector<int>& costs) {
        vector<int> dp(days.size() + 1, -1);

        int index = 0;

        return solveMem(days, costs, dp, index);
    }
};
```

# **Queue Solution**

# Approach
Sliding window.
Maximum size of month queue can be 30.
Maximum size of week queue can be 7.

**Time and Space Complexity**: both are O(1)

```
class Solution {
public:
    int mincostTickets(vector<int>& days, vector<int>& costs) {
        int ans = 0;
        queue<pair<int, int>> week, month;

        //first part of the pair will indicate the day, and the second part will indicate the cost on this day

        for(auto day : days)
        {
            //step 1 : remove expired elements from the queue
            while(!week.empty() && week.front().first + 7 <= day)
            {
                week.pop();
            }
            while(!month.empty() && month.front().first + 30 <= day)
            {
                month.pop();
            }

            //step 2: push current day's cost
            week.push(make_pair(day, ans + costs[1]));
            month.push(make_pair(day, ans + costs[2]));

            //step 3: update the ans
            ans = min(ans + costs[0], min(week.front().second, month.front().second));
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

