# Approach
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
***Why Greedy doesn't work:***
- The simplest greedy approach would be similar to the fractional knapsack, taking the best cost per day plan.
- But, The solution doesn't work because the plan must be taken in total we cannot take it per day, *Example: For 7 days plan we must take all 7 days cost even though we are using only 4 days in that plan. So, the total cost would not be reduced to per day*.
I don't know if it was only me or if anyone would consider greedy as their first approach. This was for people who had trouble finding why greedy wouldn't work.

# Greedy Code
*Note: This is just an example for greedy.(However, I am not a good programmer. Any changes to the code are appreciated)*
```
class Solution {
public:
    int mincostTickets(vector<int>& days, vector<int>& costs) {
        // we must pay the all days plan in total so, greedy fails here
        int start = 0;
        int ans = 0;
        while(start < days.size()){
        //     naive approach -> next 30 days if it has least cost per day for 30, 7 or 1 day cost take it --> greedy
        int cnt7=0,cnt30=0;
        for(int i=start; i<days.size(); i++){
            if(days[i]-days[start] < 7){
                     cnt7++;
                 }
                 if(days[i]-days[start] < 30){
                     cnt30++;
                 }else{
                     break;
                 }
             }
             // cost per day
             double c1 = (double)costs[0], c2 = (double)(costs[1]*7)/cnt7, c3 = (double)(costs[2]*30)/cnt30;
             // take day 1 and proceed
             if(c1 < c2 && c1 < c3){
                 ans += costs[0];
                 start++;
             }else if(c2 < c3){
                 ans += costs[1];
                 start += cnt7;
             }else{
                 ans += costs[2];
                 start += cnt30;
             }
         }
         return ans;
    }
};
```

# Approach
**Working Solution (Dynamic Programming):**
- Each day of the 'dp' array represents the optimal money spent till that day.
- For the 1-day plan, it is easy to get the optimal cost for a particular day i.e. 1-day plan cost + dp[i-1](optimal cost till previous day).
- For the 7-day plan and 30-day plan, the minimum cost affects the next upcoming 30 or 7 days. So, Take the minimum cost and update the 'dp' array to have minimum costs for upcoming days. This ensures that we are not taking multiple plans at the same time. 
- For the first day, we don't have any minimum value to take for the previous day. So, make sure to set the previous cost to 0 before proceeding. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: **O(number of days * 30)**
For each day we can atmost look for next 30 days.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: **O(number of days)**
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The solution described is not the best solution. May have better solutions than this.

# Dynamic Programming Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int mincostTickets(vector<int>& days, vector<int>& costs) {
        // dynamic programming knapsack and LIS kind-of problem
        vector<int> dp(days.size(), INT_MAX);
        for(int i=0; i<days.size(); i++){
            // cost for a day
            if(i == 0)
                dp[i] = costs[0];
            else
                dp[i] = min(dp[i-1]+costs[0], dp[i]);

            // cost for 7-day or 30-day plan
            int prevCost = 0;
            if(i != 0)
                prevCost = dp[i-1];
            for(int j=i; j<days.size(); j++){
                if(days[j]-days[i] < 7){
                    dp[j] = min(prevCost+costs[1], dp[j]);
                }
                if(days[j]-days[i] < 30){
                    dp[j] = min(prevCost+costs[2], dp[j]);
                }else{
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[days.size()-1];
    }
};
```

