Note: this solution uses Javascript arrays which means insert/delete options will be O(n), resulting in an overall time complexity of O(n^2). However, by using a library such as Collections.js, you will have a similar API with O(1) insertion/deletion to the beginning and the end of the deques.

```
/**
 * @param {number[]} nums
 * @param {number} limit
 * @return {number}
 */
var longestSubarray = function (nums, limit = 10) {
  let minDeque = []
  let maxDeque = []
  let max = 1;
  let l = 0;

  for (let h = 0; h < nums.length; h++) {
    // add new h to min and max deques
    // remove all elements that are greater than nums[h]
    while (minDeque[minDeque.length - 1] > nums[h]) {
      minDeque.pop()
    }
    minDeque.push(nums[h])
    // remove all elements that are lower than nums[h]
    while (maxDeque[maxDeque.length - 1] < nums[h]) {
      maxDeque.pop()
    }
    maxDeque.push(nums[h])

    if (maxDeque[0] - minDeque[0] > limit) {
      // increase l by 1
      while (maxDeque[0] - minDeque[0] > limit) {
        // update min and max queues
        minDeque[0] === nums[l] && minDeque.shift() 
        maxDeque[0] === nums[l] && maxDeque.shift() 
        l++
      }
    }

    max = Math.max(h - l + 1, max);
  }

  return max;
};
```

Explanation:
The structure of the problem is a classic sliding window question. We want to maintain a sliding window `[l,h]`, which moves through the `nums` array, and want to check that the `max - min` in the window satisfies the limit constraint. If so, then the longest subarray length can be updated to `h - l + 1` given that it's the new longest subarray.

The tricky part of the question lies in how to store the max and min per window. If we were to derive the max and min in each subarray per iteration, that would be an O(n) operation, so we need to do this in a more clever way.

We can turn getting the max/min of the subarray into an O(1) operation by storing the potential candidates for the max and mins of the subarrays into two deques (double-ended queue).

* `maxDeque` - stores candidates to be max of sliding window. This deque is in monotonically decreasing order. `maxDeque[0]` is the max of the current window
* `minDeque` - stores candidates to be min of sliding window. This deque is in monotonically increasing order. `minDeque[0]` is the min of the current window

Consider the input array `[4, 10, 3, 20, 4]` with a limit of 10.

1. The sliding window starts off with `[4]`. So we push 4 into the min and max deques.
    minDeque: [4]
    maxDeque: [4]

2. Next, the sliding window becomes `[4, 10]`. Before we push 10 into the min and max deques, we pop out all elements that don't satisfy the constraints. In the min deque, this would be any value that is greater than 10. In the max queue, this would be any value that is less than 10. What this is essentially doing is saying 10 is a potential min candidate now (if we slide `l` up and the window becomes `[10]`. We're also removing the 4 from `maxDeque` as 4 can no longer be a max candidate, since we already have a 10 to its right.
    minDeque: [4, 10]
	maxDeque: [10]

3. Continue for sliding window = `[4, 10, 3]`. Notice how 4 is no longer in any of the deques and it doesn't matter, since it will neither be a min nor a max with 10 and 3 to its right.
    minDeque: [3]
	maxDeque: [10, 3]

4. Continue until the end...updating the maximum length on each iteration.

