solutions.content:
### intuition:  
The idea is to traverse forward through the array whilst keeping the maximum and minimum values (max and min), and make sure that the difference between them is always less than or equal to Limit. 
When running into a number which contradicts this logic, counter is set back to value 1 (Which is the lowest possible answer), and we'll have to traverse through the array backwards and take into account numbers that we might have missed on, that were present earlier in the iteration, or else we won't get the actual result.

This is best demonstrated when running into an array like **[10,1,2,4,7,2]**, with **Limit=5** :  
in this case, we'll start with '10' as our max and min, iterate to '1', and since the difference is 9 which is bigger than Limit, We'll continue the iteration when now both our Max and Min values are '1'.
Continue iterating through '2' and '4', and now our counter value is at '3' - BUT when running into '7', min's value is still '1', and max's value is 7.
The difference between them is 6 which is bigger than Limit's 5, so we'll set counter back to default value, and set 7 as both our Max and Min values and continue iterating forward.
Hold on - but what about '2' and '4' who came before '7' but also needs to be taken into account?
Therefore, we'll have to traverse BACKWARDS using integer 'j' as long as the previous number doesn't break our condition regarding Limit, and increment counter accordingly.
After we're done with the backwards iteration, we'll just continue iterating forward from the same place we left off as long as the condition applies, until we finish the loop.

FINALLY, if we happen to run into a number which breaks our condition but the current 'ans'  variable is bigger than the length of what's left to iterate, we'll just break from the loop, and return the correct result.

```

class Solution {
    public int longestSubarray(int[] nums, int limit) {
        int ans = 1;
        int counter = 0;
        int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        for(int i=0; i<nums.length; i++){ 
            max = Math.max(max,nums[i]);
            min = Math.min(min,nums[i]);
            if(max-min<=limit){ //Forward iteration as long as the condition applies
                counter++;
                ans = Math.max(counter, ans);   
            }
            else{ 
                if(ans-1 > nums.length-i) break;
				max = nums[i];
                min = nums[i];
                int j = i;
                counter = 1;        
				//Backwards iteration to take into account the numbers we might have missed on
                while(--j>=0 && Math.abs(max-nums[j])<=limit & Math.abs(min-nums[j])<=limit){
                    max = Math.max(max,nums[j]);
                    min = Math.min(min,nums[j]);
                    counter++;                                        
                }
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```

