solutions.content:
The idea is to use left and right pointers to move the subarray window. Within a window, you need to track the min and max values. If the difference between min and max is within limits, then the subarray is valid. 

Advance the right pointer in each iteration. This adds new elements to the subarray and ensures we reach the end of the input. 

When a new element is included in the subarray, we need to perform 2 checks, is the new element lesser than min or is the new element greater than max. If the new element doesn't affect min or max, then the subarray is still valid.

By not it's clear you advance the right pointer in each iteration, but it's not clear when to advance the left pointer.

When the new element included in the subarray is lesser than min or greater than max, then we have to advance the left pointer to find the next valid window.

If the new element is either lesser than min or greater than max, move the left pointer toward right until, the difference between the elements between left and right pointers is wihin the limit.

After you have found the new valid subarray, if the new element is lesser than min, then you need to
1. Find the new max in the subarray.
2. Update the min to the new min.

On the other hand, if the new elemet is greater than max, then you need to
1. Find the new min in the subarray.
2. Update the max to the new max.

Time Complexity is O(N)
The while loop consistently move the right pointer toward the end -> N.
In the worst case, for each move of right pointer, the left pointer moves once so the subarray size is always 1. Example: [1,2,3] limit = 0. This means each element in the array is visited twice so time complexity becomes 2N.

Asymptotically, the complexity is O(N).

```
public class Solution {
    public int LongestSubarray(int[] nums, int limit) {
        int max = nums[0], min = nums[0];
        int left = 0, right = 0;
        int maxSize = 0, size = 0;

        while (right < nums.Length) {
            if(nums[right] < min) {
                min = nums[right];
                if(Math.Abs(max - nums[right]) > limit) {
                    left = FindLeft(left, right, limit, nums);
                    max = FindMax(left, right, nums);
                }
            }
            else if(nums[right] > max) {
                max = nums[right];
                if(Math.Abs(min - nums[right]) > limit) {
                    left = FindLeft(left, right, limit, nums);
                    min = FindMin(left, right, nums);
                }
            }

            size = right - left + 1;
            maxSize = Math.Max(maxSize, size);
            right++;
        }

        return maxSize;
    }

    public static int FindMin(int left, int right, int[] nums) {
        int min = nums[left];
        for(int i=left; i<=right; i++) {
            min = Math.Min(nums[i], min);
        }

        return min;
    }

    public static int FindMax(int left, int right, int[] nums) {
        int max = nums[left];
        for(int i=left; i<=right; i++) {
            max = Math.Max(nums[i], max);
        }

        return max;
    }

    public static int FindLeft(int left, int right, int limit, int[] nums) {
        int newLeft = left;

        for(int i=left; i<=right; i++) {
            if(Math.Abs(nums[right] - nums[i]) > limit) {
                newLeft = i;
            }
        }

        if(Math.Abs(nums[right] - nums[newLeft]) > limit) {
            newLeft++;
        }

        return newLeft;
    }
}
```

